{
  "version": 2,
  "name": "DigitalDrift",
  "description": "Digital Drift — a faithful node-graph rebuild of the Latent Space website background mosh, built from composable atoms (no wgsl_compute monolith). The website's single fragment pass decomposes into a summed UV offset that resamples the source once, organised into two readable groups. `Drift Field` is the motion engine: the per-band horizontal slide is node.scanline_jitter_field in Slide motion (smooth value-noise drift, every band, ungated, band count = `bands`); the organic domain-warp flow is node.math (time * speed) → two more node.math (× +0.065 / -0.065, giving the website's t = u_time*0.13 at speed 2) → two node.noise in the Value type (the 123.34/456.21/45.32 value-noise hash) sampled at uv*3 ± t → node.pack_channels (R/G) → node.scale_offset_texture(0.028, -0.014) = (value_noise - 0.5)*0.028; node.mix(Add) sums the flow offset (RG) and the slide offset (R) into one field. `Warp & Split` applies it: node.remap(Relative) warps the source by the summed offset in a single resample, then node.radial_offset_field(Linear) → node.chromatic_displace adds the horizontal RGB fringe at the seams. A top-level node.mix(Lerp, Drift) crossfades the whole effect back over the untouched source so Drift=0 is a clean passthrough (skipMode onZero). Two node.value hubs fan the cards: Drift → the slide amount + the final crossfade; Speed → both the flow time-scale and the slide rate, so one Speed knob accelerates the entire motion together. The value-noise field is the literal website function — the Value type on node.noise and the matching hash on node.scanline_jitter_field's Slide mode carry the same constants — so this is the actual effect, not a lookalike. Divergences vs the website: (a) the chromatic split is a separate post pass on the warped image (one extra bilinear tap, visually negligible) rather than folded into the same fetch; (b) the website's occasional glitch-gate `g` (gated big shift + g-scaled chromatic) is omitted — Digital Drift is the calm continuous form; add a second node.scanline_jitter_field in Tear mode for the spiky accent; (c) source UVs are canvas [0,1] (the clip already fills the canvas) rather than the website's aspect-cover branch. Flow time comes from system.generator_input.time; the slide reads FrameTime.seconds internally. The groups flatten to a graph byte-identical in behaviour to the ungrouped form; card bindings reach inner nodes by stable nodeId, so grouping never touches the performance surface.",
